<div style="background-color: #FFF9F0; padding: 40px; font-family: 'Georgia', serif; color: #333;">
    <h2 style="text-align: center; color: #2E7D32; font-weight: bold; font-size: 32px;">All About Your Dogs</h2>

    <!-- Feeding Section -->
    <section style="margin-top: 30px; font-family: Georgia, serif;">


        <div style="display: flex; gap: 20px; align-items: flex-start;">
            <div style="flex: 3;">
                <h3 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 10px;">Feeding</h3>
                <p style="text-align: justify; line-height: 1.6;">
                    Feeding your dog varies based on age, size, activity level, and food type. Younger, active dogs burn more calories, so they need more protein and fat. Older, less active dogs require fewer calories. Commercial pet food feeding guidelines should be used as a rough guideline, as many dogs are overweight due to incorrect portion sizes. Large breed dogs require less food and small breed dogs require more. Puppies should be fed at least three times a day until their food requirements level off as they mature. By five or six months, their feeding schedule can be reduced to twice a day. If your puppy is finicky, add warm water to dry food to encourage eating. Feeding too much can lead to pudgy pups, bone abnormalities, and other health issues. Gradually decrease food intake if your puppy appears to be gaining too much weight, but increase portions if ribs are showing. Consult your vet for guidance on proper weight or appearance. Active adults require moderate exercise, but their energy needs may be greater than those of sedentary dogs. Nutritional requirements will remain the same during their young adult life.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div style="flex: 1; display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: end; gap: 15px;">
                <img src="~/Content/Images/DogCare/DogCare_1.png" alt="Icon" style="width: 60px; border-radius: 50%; " />
                <img src="~/Content/Images/DogCare/DogCare_2.png" alt="Feeding Dog" style="width: 180px; height: 180px; object-fit: cover; border-radius: 50%; " />
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>


    <section style="margin-top: 30px; font-family: Georgia, serif;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 20px;">

            <!-- Image Circle -->
            <div style="flex: 1; display: flex; justify-content: center;">
                <img src="~/Content/Images/DogCare/DogCare_3.png" alt="Dog Command Training"
                     style="width: 180px; height: 180px; object-fit: cover; border-radius: 50%; " />
            </div>

            <!-- Text Content -->
            <div style="flex: 3;">
                <h4 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 8px;">Grooming</h4>
                <p style="text-align: justify; line-height: 1.6;">
                    Regular brushing removes dirt and debris, keeps the dog's coat shiny and clean. Bathing when needed prevents skin and temperature issues. Clipping helps maintain manageable coat length. Clean the dog's ears, avoid correcting them, and be positive. Prepare your dog for professional grooming by bathing at home and using a dog-friendly brush.
                </p>

                <h4 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 8px;">Handling</h4>
                <p style="text-align: justify; line-height: 1.6;">
                    To handle your dog effectively, be gentle, consistent, patient, use positive reinforcement, keep training sessions short, choose a quiet environment, introduce new people, and gradually introduce new locations. Use treats and praise when your dog does well, and gradually introduce new people and locations to ensure a successful training experience.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>




    <section style="margin-top: 40px; font-family: Georgia, serif;">
        <!-- Section Title -->
        <h2 style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: bold; font-size: 22px;">Dog Training Guide</h2>

        <!-- Text and Image Layout -->
        <div style="display: flex; gap: 30px; align-items: center;">

            <!-- Text Column -->
            <div style="flex: 3;">
                <h4 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 8px;">Teach your dogs for command</h4>
                <p style="text-align: justify; line-height: 1.6;">
                    The word "no" can have various meanings in humans, but it is often used to express denial or refusal in response to questions. In training dogs, it can be used as a pre-punishment cue or a reward for holding a position. However, it should never mean that the dog will be hurt or in trouble. The "stay" command, which instructs a dog to remain stationary until released, can be effective if it is more rewarding. Most people make the mistake of teaching the dog to break the position rather than hold it, which can make the command less reliable. To teach the "stay" command effectively, rewards should be given to the dog for holding the position, such as food, verbal praise, objects, or play time.
                </p>

                <h4 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 8px;">How Much Should You Keep Your Dog Outdoors?</h4>
                <p style="text-align: justify; line-height: 1.6;">
                    Urban dogs often enjoy a three-walk-a-day schedule for exercise, socializing, and elimination. However, some dog guardians use the yard as a crutch, turning it into Phydeau’s entire world. This can lead to social isolation and difficulty in training the dog. Dogs who are kept outside experience excessive barking and howling, and may engage in rapturous leaps and vocalizations when family members enter the yard. Over time, an isolated outdoor dog becomes independent and difficult to train. If your dog enjoys spending time outside, a doghouse can provide protection from the elements. Make sure the opening faces into the wind during the coldest months, hang carpet strips over the doorway, and provide good insulated bedding. Clean the place out every few months to ensure no other beasties have set up house.
                </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Centered Image Column -->
            <div style="flex: 1; display: flex; justify-content: center;">
                <img src="~/Content/Images/DogCare/DogCare_4.png" alt="Dog Command Training"
                     style="width: 180px; height: 180px; object-fit: cover; border-radius: 50%; " />
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>



    <!-- Health & Wellness -->
    <section style="margin-top: 40px;">
        <h3 style="color: #1B5E20;">Dog Health and Wellness Information</h3>
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 20px;">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/DogCare/DogCare_5.png" alt="Health and Wellness" style="width: 180px; height: 180px; object-fit: cover; border-radius: 50%; " />
            <div style="flex: 3;">
                <h4 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 8px;">Health Tips:</h4>
                <p> Annual visits to your veterinarian are crucial for maintaining your dog's health. They can help you identify any health issues and discuss any changes in your dog's condition. Regular vaccinations, such as Leptospirosis, are essential for keeping your dog safe. Encourage your dog to exercise daily, and consider taking the Canine Good Citizen test (CGC) for good behavior. Obesity is a common issue, and proper exercise and a balanced diet are essential. Dental and gum health is also crucial for dogs, and proper oral hygiene is essential. Be aware of potential toxins in your home and set boundaries to prevent accidents. Microchipping your dog or wearing tags can help identify and return them to you. Lastly, include your dog in daily activities, hugging and playing with them, as they love being part of your family</p>

            </div>

        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Nutrition & Diet -->
    <section style="margin-top: 40px;">
        <h3 style="color: #1B5E20;">Dog Nutrition and Diet</h3>

        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 20px;">
            <div style="flex: 3;">

                <p>Choose a complete and balanced diet. Look for dog food labeled as "complete" to ensure it provides all the necessary nutrients.  Proper portioning Pay attention to the recommended serving size on the food packaging and adjust based on your dog's weight and activity level.  Feeding schedule Most adult dogs should be fed once or twice a day, with larger breeds often benefiting from two meals to prevent overeating. Treats in moderation Limit treats to no more than 10% of your dog's daily calorie intake. Healthy fats Include sources of healthy fats like fish oil or chicken fat for a shiny coat and optimal health. Fruits and vegetables Offer a variety of dog-friendly fruits and vegetables in moderation as a source of vitamins and fiber. Avoid human food Do not feed your dog table scraps or human food that can be harmful to their health. Monitor weight Regularly check your dog's weight and adjust their food intake if they become overweight. </p>
            </div>


            <!-- Centered Image Column -->
            <div style="flex: 1; display: flex; justify-content: center;">
                <img src="~/Content/Images/DogCare/DogCare_6.png" alt="Dog Command Training"
                     style="width: 180px; height: 180px; object-fit: cover; border-radius: 50%; " />
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-top: 40px;">


        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 20px;">
            <!-- Centered Image Column -->
            <div style="flex: 1; display: flex; justify-content: center;">
                <img src="~/Content/Images/DogCare/DogCare_7.png" alt="Dog Command Training"
                     style="width: 180px; height: 180px; object-fit: cover; border-radius: 50%; " />
            </div>
            <div style="flex: 3;">
                <h4>How Much Should You Feed Your Dog?</h4>
                <p>The food requirements of dogs vary based on their health, activity level, and age. For puppies, they should be fed at least three times a day until their food requirements level off as they mature. For active adults, moderate exercise is essential for their overall health. However, when a dog is less active, their food requirements decrease. To prevent gastric bloat, it is recommended to gradually change to a lower energy, less nutrient-dense dog food. Adults should maintain a stable weight and well-proportioned body. Appetite may vary, but not if it persists for several days or shows signs of weight loss or illness. Senior dogs should be fed according to their overall health and level of activity, as less active dogs can quickly gain weight if not properly cared for. It is crucial to provide fresh water and rest for the dog to maintain their health and well-being. </p>
            </div>



        </div>
    </section>
</div>
